VALUES
(43, 18, 1, 10, 15, 23, 23, 'brook Cedron', 'Connection of Brook Cedron and Kidron', 'This connection highlights the movement of Jesus and King David over a brook, symbolizing a moment of transition and sorrow. Both passages emphasize the act of crossing the brook as significant in their respective narratives.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 1, 40, 26, 36, 36, 'a garden', 'Connection of Jesus'' Location', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' movement to a garden, highlighting the significance of this location in the narrative. John mentions ''a garden'' while Matthew specifies it as ''Gethsemane'', connecting the two accounts of Jesus'' actions before his arrest.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 1, 41, 14, 32, 32, 'a garden', 'Connection of Garden and Prayer', 'This connection highlights the setting of a garden where Jesus engages in prayer with his disciples. Both passages emphasize the significance of this location in the events leading up to his crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 1, 42, 22, 39, 40, 'where was a garden', 'Jesus in the Garden', 'Both passages describe Jesus going to a garden or a place of prayer with his disciples. This connection highlights the significance of the location as a setting for Jesus'' impending trials and the disciples'' need for vigilance in prayer.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 1, 43, 18, 26, 26, NULL, 'Connection of Garden References', 'Both passages emphasize the garden where Jesus entered with his disciples. The mention of the garden in John 18:1 directly links to the inquiry about Jesus being seen there in John 18:26.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 1, 1, 3, 23, 23, 'garden', 'Garden of Eden and Gethsemane', 'Both passages emphasize a garden setting where significant actions occur. In Genesis, the garden represents a departure from paradise, while in John, Jesus enters a garden before his arrest, symbolizing a pivotal moment in his mission.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 1, 11, 15, 13, 13, 'brook Cedron', 'Connection through the Brook Kidron', 'This connection highlights the significance of the brook Kidron in both passages. In John 18:1, Jesus crosses the brook Cedron, which is often identified with Kidron, while in 1 Kings 15:13, the brook Kidron is a site of idol destruction, emphasizing themes of purity and separation from idolatry.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 2, 42, 21, 37, 37, 'with his disciples', 'Connection of Betrayal and Location', 'This connection highlights the significance of the mount of Olives as a place where Jesus frequently met with his disciples, as noted in both passages. Judas''s knowledge of this location in John 18:2 and Jesus''s nightly retreat there in Luke 21:37 emphasize the importance of this setting in the events leading to the betrayal.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 2, 42, 22, 39, 39, 'for Jesus ofttimes resorted thither', 'Judas and the Mount of Olives', 'This connection highlights Judas''s knowledge of Jesus''s frequent visits to a specific location, the Mount of Olives. Both passages emphasize Jesus''s habitual presence in this area with his disciples, which ultimately leads to the betrayal.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 2, 41, 11, 11, 12, 'for Jesus ofttimes resorted thither', 'Jesus'' Frequent Visits to Bethany', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' habitual presence in Bethany, as noted in John 18:2, where he often resorted there with his disciples. Mark 11:11-12 indicates that Jesus entered Jerusalem and then returned to Bethany, reinforcing the significance of this location in his ministry.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 3, 43, 18, 12, 12, 'band of men', 'Connection of Arresting Jesus', 'This connection highlights the sequence of events surrounding Jesus'' arrest. The ''band'' mentioned in both passages indicates the group that apprehended Jesus, linking the initial approach to the subsequent binding of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 3, 42, 22, 47, 53, 'Judas then, having received a band', 'Betrayal and Arrest of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Judas''s betrayal of Jesus, with John highlighting the armed group that came to arrest Him, while Luke details Judas''s approach and kiss as a sign of betrayal. This connection highlights the coordinated effort of the religious leaders to apprehend Jesus.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 3, 19, 3, 1, 2, NULL, 'Opposition and Betrayal', 'This connection highlights the theme of rising opposition. In John 18:3, Judas leads a group against Jesus, paralleling the troubles expressed in Psalms 3:1-2, where many rise up against the psalmist.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 3, 19, 22, 12, 12, NULL, 'Surrounding Forces in Distress', 'This connection highlights the theme of being beset by hostile forces. In John 18:3, Judas brings a band of men, while Psalms 22:12 describes being surrounded by strong bulls, symbolizing opposition and danger.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 3, 44, 1, 16, 16, NULL, 'Connection Between Judas and Betrayal', 'This connection highlights Judas''s role in the betrayal of Jesus, as seen in both passages. John 18:3 describes Judas leading those who came to arrest Jesus, while Acts 1:16 refers to him as the guide to those who took Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 3, 40, 26, 47, 56, 'a band of men', 'Judas''s Betrayal and Arrest', 'Both passages emphasize Judas''s role in betraying Jesus, as he arrives with a group to arrest Him. The mention of ''a band of men'' in John parallels the ''great multitude'' in Matthew, highlighting the coordinated effort to seize Jesus.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 3, 41, 14, 43, 50, 'a band of men and officers', 'Judas'' Betrayal and Arrest', 'Both passages emphasize Judas'' role in the betrayal of Jesus, highlighting his actions in leading a group to arrest Him. The mention of a ''great multitude'' and ''weapons'' in both texts underscores the violent intent behind the arrest.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 4, 43, 13, 1, 1, NULL, 'Jesus'' Knowledge of His Fate', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' awareness of his impending departure. In John 18:4, he knows all things that should come upon him, while in John 13:1, he knows his hour has come to leave the world.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 4, 43, 18, 7, 7, 'Whom seek ye?', 'Inquiry of Jesus'' Identity', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' repeated question, ''Whom seek ye?'' in both passages. It emphasizes the focus on the identity of Jesus as he confronts those who have come to arrest him.', 'keyword', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 4, 19, 27, 3, 3, NULL, 'Confidence in Adversity', 'This connection highlights the theme of facing challenges without fear. Both passages emphasize a steadfast heart in the face of impending trials.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 4, 44, 2, 28, 28, 'knowing all things that should come upon him', 'Connection of Knowledge and Joy', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine knowledge and its impact on human experience. In John 18:4, Jesus demonstrates awareness of what is to come, while Acts 2:28 speaks of joy derived from God''s presence, suggesting a link between understanding and spiritual fulfillment.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 4, 44, 20, 22, 23, 'knowing all things that should come upon him', 'Knowledge of Future Trials', 'This connection highlights the awareness of impending trials. Jesus knows what will happen to him, while Paul is aware of the bonds and afflictions awaiting him, indicating a shared theme of foreknowledge of suffering.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 4, 11, 18, 10, 10, 'Whom seek ye?', 'Seeking and Knowledge', 'This connection highlights the theme of seeking, as both passages involve characters actively searching for someone. In John 18:4, Jesus asks, ''Whom seek ye?'' while in 1 Kings 18:10, the search for Elijah is emphasized.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 4, 16, 6, 11, 11, 'whom seek ye', 'Courage in the Face of Danger', 'This connection highlights the theme of courage in both passages. Jesus, aware of his impending suffering, confronts his captors, while Nehemiah refuses to flee, demonstrating steadfastness in the face of threats.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 5, 23, 3, 9, 9, NULL, 'Connection of Sin and Betrayal', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal and the acknowledgment of sin. In John 18:5, Judas''s presence signifies betrayal, while Isaiah 3:9 speaks of openly declaring sin, paralleling the consequences of both actions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 5, 24, 8, 12, 12, 'I am he', 'Shame and Betrayal Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of shame associated with betrayal. In John 18:5, Judas stands with those who seek to arrest Jesus, while Jeremiah 8:12 discusses a lack of shame in committing abominations, suggesting a parallel in the moral failure of betrayal.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 5, 40, 2, 23, 23, 'Jesus of Nazareth', 'Connection of Nazareth References', 'This connection highlights the significance of Nazareth in both passages. In John, Jesus identifies himself as ''Jesus of Nazareth,'' while Matthew emphasizes that he shall be called a Nazarene, linking his identity to this location.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 5, 40, 21, 11, 11, 'Jesus of Nazareth', 'Connection of Jesus of Nazareth', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' identity as ''Jesus of Nazareth.'' The mention of Nazareth in both contexts highlights his origin and public recognition.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 5, 43, 1, 46, 46, 'Jesus of Nazareth', 'Connection Between Nazareth References', 'This connection highlights the significance of Nazareth as a point of skepticism and revelation. In John 1:46, Nathanael questions if anything good can come from Nazareth, while in John 18:5, Jesus identifies himself as Jesus of Nazareth, affirming his identity despite the doubt.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 5, 43, 19, 19, 19, 'Jesus of Nazareth', 'Identity of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of Jesus as ''Jesus of Nazareth.'' In John 18:5, Jesus identifies himself, while in John 19:19, Pilate labels him, reinforcing this key aspect of his identity.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 6, 19, 27, 2, 2, NULL, 'Falling Before Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of enemies stumbling and falling in the presence of power. In John 18:6, the adversaries fall when confronted by Jesus'' declaration, while Psalm 27:2 describes foes stumbling when attacking the psalmist.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 6, 19, 70, 2, 3, NULL, 'Backward Movement in Context', 'This connection highlights the theme of being turned backward in both passages. In John 18:6, the men fall backward upon Jesus'' declaration, while Psalms 70:2-3 calls for those seeking harm to be turned backward.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 6, 12, 1, 9, 15, 'I am he', 'Divine Authority and Power', 'Both passages emphasize the power of divine authority, as seen when Jesus declares ''I am he'' and causes those who seek him to fall back, paralleling Elijah''s demonstration of authority when fire consumes the captains. This connection highlights the theme of God''s presence eliciting fear and submission.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 6, 44, 4, 29, 30, 'I am he', 'Boldness in the Face of Threats', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine power in both passages. In John 18:6, Jesus'' declaration causes a physical reaction, while Acts 4:29-30 emphasizes the need for boldness in proclaiming His name and performing signs and wonders.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 6, 42, 9, 54, 56, 'I am he', 'Divine Authority and Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority and the response of those who encounter it. In John 18:6, the powerful declaration ''I am he'' causes a physical reaction, while in Luke 9:54-56, the disciples'' desire to call down fire reflects a misunderstanding of Jesus'' mission and authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 7, 43, 18, 4, 4, 'Whom seek ye?', 'Question of Identity', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus asking, ''Whom seek ye?'' This connection highlights the moment of confrontation between Jesus and those who came to arrest him.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 8, 43, 10, 28, 28, 'let these go their way', 'Protection of Believers', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' assurance of safety for His followers. In both passages, there is an emphasis on Jesus'' role in safeguarding those who seek Him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 8, 23, 53, 6, 6, 'let these go their way', 'Sheep and Their Way', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of individuals going astray. In John 18:8, Jesus indicates that those seeking him should let others go their way, paralleling Isaiah 53:6, which speaks of all turning to their own way.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 8, 40, 26, 56, 56, 'let these go their way', 'Disciples'' Abandonment of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the moment of Jesus'' arrest when he identifies himself, leading to the disciples'' abandonment. Both passages emphasize the fulfillment of prophecy regarding the disciples forsaking Jesus.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 8, 41, 14, 50, 52, 'let these go their way', 'Abandonment and Flight', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of abandonment during Jesus'' arrest. In John, Jesus instructs that those seeking him should let his followers go, while Mark describes how all his disciples forsook him and fled, highlighting their fear and desertion.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 8, 43, 13, 1, 1, 'I have told you that I am he', 'Connection of Jesus'' Departure', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' awareness of his impending departure. In John 18:8, he indicates a protective instinct for his followers, while John 13:1 highlights his knowledge of the hour to leave the world.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 8, 46, 10, 13, 13, 'let these go their way', 'Temptation and Deliverance Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of deliverance in times of distress. In John 18:8, Jesus seeks to protect his disciples from harm, while 1 Corinthians 10:13 assures believers that God provides a way to escape temptation.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 8, 47, 12, 9, 9, 'let these go their way', 'Strength in Weakness', 'This connection highlights the theme of reliance on Christ''s strength in moments of vulnerability. In John 18:8, Jesus emphasizes the need for protection of others, while 2 Corinthians 12:9 speaks to finding strength through grace in weakness.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 9, 43, 17, 12, 12, 'of them which thou gavest me have I lost none', 'Connection of Preservation Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the preservation of those given to Jesus, stating that none are lost except for the son of perdition. This connection highlights the fulfillment of Jesus'' promise to keep His followers safe.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 10, 41, 14, 47, 47, NULL, 'Peter''s Act of Violence', 'Both passages emphasize the act of drawing a sword and cutting off a servant''s ear, highlighting a moment of violence during Jesus'' arrest. The specific action and the involvement of a high priest''s servant create a direct link between the two accounts.', 'parallel', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 10, 40, 26, 51, 54, NULL, 'Peter''s Act of Violence', 'Both passages emphasize Peter''s action of drawing a sword and striking a servant of the high priest, resulting in the severing of an ear. This connection highlights the theme of violence in the face of arrest and Jesus'' subsequent admonition against such actions.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 10, 42, 22, 49, 51, 'cut off his right ear', 'Peter''s Attack on Malchus', 'Both passages emphasize Simon Peter''s action of cutting off the servant''s ear, highlighting a moment of violence during Jesus'' arrest. Additionally, both accounts mention the servant''s name, Malchus, linking the events directly.', 'parallel', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 10, 43, 18, 26, 26, NULL, 'Connection of Malchus and Peter', 'This connection highlights the relationship between Peter''s violent act and the subsequent identification of him by Malchus''s kinsman. Both passages emphasize the significance of the ear being cut off and its impact on the narrative.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 10, 41, 14, 30, 30, NULL, 'Peter''s Actions and Denial', 'This connection highlights Peter''s impulsive behavior in both passages. In John, Peter draws a sword, while in Mark, he is warned about his impending denial, showcasing a contrast between his boldness and future cowardice.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 10, 42, 22, 33, 33, NULL, 'Peter''s Commitment to Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Peter''s readiness to defend Jesus. In John, Peter acts with violence to protect Jesus, while in Luke, he expresses his willingness to follow Jesus to death.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 11, 40, 20, 22, 22, 'the cup which my Father hath given me', 'Connection of the Cup', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of the ''cup'' that Jesus must drink. In John, Jesus refers to the cup given by the Father, while in Matthew, He questions the disciples about their ability to drink from the same cup. This connection highlights the shared theme of suffering and sacrifice.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 11, 40, 26, 39, 39, 'the cup which my Father hath given me', 'Connection of the Cup Motif', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''cup,'' representing Jesus'' impending suffering. In John, Jesus acknowledges the necessity of drinking the cup given by the Father, while in Matthew, He expresses a desire for the cup to pass, highlighting the tension between His will and the Father''s.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 11, 43, 20, 17, 17, 'the cup which my Father hath given me', 'Connection of Divine Authority', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' submission to God''s will in both passages. In John 18:11, Jesus refers to the ''cup'' given by the Father, while in John 20:17, He speaks of ascending to ''my Father'' and ''your Father,'' emphasizing His relationship with God and His mission.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 11, 43, 12, 27, 28, 'the cup which my Father hath given me', 'Jesus'' Acceptance of His Fate', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' acceptance of his impending suffering. In John 18:11, Jesus acknowledges the necessity of drinking the cup given by the Father, while in John 12:27-28, he expresses his purpose for coming to this hour despite his troubled soul.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 11, 58, 12, 2, 2, 'the cup which my Father hath given me', 'Endurance and Obedience to God', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' willingness to endure suffering as seen in both passages. In John 18:11, Jesus speaks of drinking the cup given by the Father, while Hebrews 12:2 emphasizes His endurance of the cross for joy set before Him.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 11, 41, 10, 38, 39, 'the cup which my Father hath given me', 'Connection of the Cup', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''the cup'' that Jesus must drink, symbolizing suffering and sacrifice. In John, Jesus refers to the cup given by the Father, while in Mark, He questions the disciples about their ability to drink from the same cup.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 11, 41, 14, 35, 36, 'the cup which my Father hath given me', 'Connection of the Cup', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''cup'' as a symbol of suffering. In John, Jesus refers to drinking the cup given by the Father, while in Mark, he expresses a desire for the cup to be taken away. This connection highlights the theme of submission to God''s will in the face of impending suffering.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 12, 40, 26, 57, 57, 'bound him', 'Arrest and Binding of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the act of taking Jesus into custody. The binding in John 18:12 and the leading away in Matthew 26:57 highlight the transition from freedom to captivity.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 12, 43, 18, 3, 3, 'band', 'Connection of Jesus'' Arrest', 'Both passages emphasize the binding of Jesus during his arrest. The ''band'' mentioned in both verses indicates the group involved in capturing him.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 12, 1, 22, 9, 9, 'bound him', 'Binding of Jesus and Isaac', 'This connection highlights the act of binding in both passages, where Jesus is ''bound'' by the officers and Isaac is ''bound'' by Abraham. Both instances reflect themes of sacrifice and submission to a higher purpose.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 12, 7, 16, 21, 21, 'bound him', 'Binding and Captivity Motif', 'This connection highlights the theme of binding and captivity in both passages. In John 18:12, Jesus is bound, while in Judges 16:21, Samson is also bound, emphasizing a shared experience of physical restraint.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 12, 40, 27, 2, 2, 'bound him', 'Binding of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the act of binding Jesus, highlighting a significant moment in his arrest and subsequent trial. This connection illustrates the continuity of events leading to his delivery to authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 12, 41, 14, 53, 53, 'bound him', 'Jesus'' Arrest and Trial', 'Both passages emphasize the moment of Jesus'' arrest and subsequent leading to the high priest. The binding of Jesus in John 18:12 connects to his being led away in Mark 14:53.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 12, 41, 15, 1, 1, 'bound him', 'Binding of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the act of binding Jesus by authorities. This connection highlights the transition from his arrest to the formal delivery to Pilate.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 13, 43, 18, 24, 24, NULL, 'Connection between Annas and Caiaphas', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between Annas and Caiaphas, highlighting Annas''s role in sending Jesus to Caiaphas. This connection illustrates the transition of Jesus from one authority to another during his trial.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 13, 40, 26, 3, 3, 'the high priest that same year', 'Connection of High Priest Figures', 'Both passages emphasize the role of Caiaphas as the high priest during the events leading to Jesus'' trial. John 18:13 mentions Caiaphas'' relationship to Annas, while Matthew 26:3 directly identifies Caiaphas as the high priest involved in the assembly against Jesus.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 13, 40, 26, 57, 57, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus'' Arrest', 'Both passages emphasize the leading of Jesus to Caiaphas, highlighting the continuity in the narrative of his arrest and trial. John specifies Annas'' role, while Matthew focuses on Caiaphas as the high priest.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 13, 42, 3, 2, 2, NULL, 'Connection of High Priest Figures', 'Both passages emphasize the roles of Annas and Caiaphas as high priests during significant events in the New Testament. This connection highlights their influence in the religious context surrounding John the Baptist and Jesus.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 13, 43, 11, 51, 51, 'high priest that same year', 'High Priest Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of Caiaphas as high priest during significant events surrounding Jesus'' trial and death. The mention of Caiaphas in John 18:13 links directly to his prophetic statement in John 11:51 about Jesus'' death for the nation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 13, 44, 4, 6, 6, NULL, 'Connection of High Priests', 'Both passages emphasize the roles of Annas and Caiaphas in the context of Jewish leadership. The mention of Annas in John 18:13 as related to Caiaphas connects directly to Acts 4:6, where both are identified as high priests.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 14, 43, 11, 49, 52, 'it was expedient that one man should die for the people', 'Caiaphas and the Prophetic Statement', 'Both passages emphasize Caiaphas''s declaration that it was expedient for one man to die for the people. This connection highlights the prophetic nature of his statement regarding Jesus''s death for the nation and beyond.', 'prophecy', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
